{"type": "user_message", "content": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>aeb11c5b66d9c9329</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_014r6t4T4XfNufBrtUAmxqHA</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>C:\\Users\\ISMAEL~1\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\claude\\C--Users-ISMAEL-MELLO-Downloads-mega-brain-premium\\tasks\\aeb11c5b66d9c9329.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Extract DNA from IF Workshop\" completed</summary>\n<result>\n\nNow I have all the content from reading the 15 sessions. Let me compile the DNA elements based on everything I've read. The files are single-line transcriptions, so I already have the full content from my reads. Let me now produce the complete YAML extraction.\n\nBased on my thorough reading of all 15 sessions, here is the complete DNA extraction:\n\n---\n\n## L1 PHILOSOPHIES (PHI-RB-087 through PHI-RB-098)\n\n```yaml\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-087\"\n        statement: \"The purpose of the content webinar is not like a regular product. It's an experience. So they love it, they feel like they leave with a lot of value.\"\n        context: \"Russell Brunson explaining the Invisible Funnel content webinar philosophy - the content is not a product pitch, it's designed for consumption and delight. Session 3, discussing webinar design.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_3.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-088\"\n        statement: \"I'm all about consumable. I want to force consumption. I want people to really enjoy it.\"\n        context: \"Russell Brunson articulating his core philosophy on forced consumption - making content so engaging people can't help but consume it, which drives the Invisible Funnel model. Session 3.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_3.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-089\"\n        statement: \"What people are looking for is a miracl", "metadata": {"session_id": "d57700cd-64b4-4d76-b212-8e7a22a24264", "transcript_path": "C:\\Users\\ISMAEL_MELLO\\.claude\\projects\\C--Users-ISMAEL-MELLO-Downloads-mega-brain-premium\\d57700cd-64b4-4d76-b212-8e7a22a24264.jsonl", "cwd": "C:\\Users\\ISMAEL_MELLO\\Downloads\\mega-brain-premium", "permission_mode": "default", "hook_event_name": "UserPromptSubmit", "prompt": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>aeb11c5b66d9c9329</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_014r6t4T4XfNufBrtUAmxqHA</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>C:\\Users\\ISMAEL~1\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\claude\\C--Users-ISMAEL-MELLO-Downloads-mega-brain-premium\\tasks\\aeb11c5b66d9c9329.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Extract DNA from IF Workshop\" completed</summary>\n<result>\n\nNow I have all the content from reading the 15 sessions. Let me compile the DNA elements based on everything I've read. The files are single-line transcriptions, so I already have the full content from my reads. Let me now produce the complete YAML extraction.\n\nBased on my thorough reading of all 15 sessions, here is the complete DNA extraction:\n\n---\n\n## L1 PHILOSOPHIES (PHI-RB-087 through PHI-RB-098)\n\n```yaml\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-087\"\n        statement: \"The purpose of the content webinar is not like a regular product. It's an experience. So they love it, they feel like they leave with a lot of value.\"\n        context: \"Russell Brunson explaining the Invisible Funnel content webinar philosophy - the content is not a product pitch, it's designed for consumption and delight. Session 3, discussing webinar design.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_3.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-088\"\n        statement: \"I'm all about consumable. I want to force consumption. I want people to really enjoy it.\"\n        context: \"Russell Brunson articulating his core philosophy on forced consumption - making content so engaging people can't help but consume it, which drives the Invisible Funnel model. Session 3.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_3.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-089\"\n        statement: \"What people are looking for is a miracle. They want to go to bed tonight and wake up tomorrow and their lives are totally transformed. They want to believe so much.\"\n        context: \"TJ Rohleder quoting Gene Schwartz's insight and expanding on it - customers buy from emotion, not logic, and they want to believe the dream is real. Session 7.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-090\"\n        statement: \"If your refunds are too low, you're not selling hard enough.\"\n        context: \"TJ Rohleder quoting Brad Amton's principle about the relationship between aggressive selling and refund rates - a healthy refund rate means you're pushing hard enough. Session 7.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-091\"\n        statement: \"People don't trust people that are too perfect. It's the people that are a little flawed. That's one of the ways you earn trust - you reveal yourself to them and that endears people to you.\"\n        context: \"TJ Rohleder sharing how revealing personal flaws (his past addiction/recovery) increased customer trust and connection. Session 7.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-092\"\n        statement: \"The impetus or emphasis was in the wrong place. I was telling the story to convince people why my product was awesome. But all that matters is to help them have the belief that one simple idea will help them.\"\n        context: \"Dagan Smith explaining his breakthrough in story selling - stop selling the product and start installing a belief. The product sells itself once the belief is established. Session 8.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_8.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-093\"\n        statement: \"If we tell a story, we go past trust and create identification. You're not you anymore. You're there experiencing it with the character.\"\n        context: \"Dagan Smith explaining why stories are superior to traditional trust-building - stories create identification where the audience becomes the character and experiences their journey. Session 8.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_8.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-094\"\n        statement: \"Given a choice between safe and happy, people will pick safe most of the time. Passion trumps fear every time.\"\n        context: \"Michael Hauge explaining inner conflict and why prospects resist transformation - their identity keeps them safe but unfulfilled. The way to overcome fear is to instill passion by showing the aftermath. Session 10.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_10.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-095\"\n        statement: \"A story is not over when the hero achieves the goal. There's one last stage you must have - the aftermath. We've got to see the after picture, the new life they are living after the journey is over.\"\n        context: \"Michael Hauge teaching the critical 'aftermath' element of storytelling - you must show the before-and-after picture for the story to have full impact. Session 10.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_10.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-096\"\n        statement: \"You can never own your customers. If you're not constantly trying to resell to them, somebody else is. They're addicts - they will always rebuy more from you than you can possibly sell to them.\"\n        context: \"TJ Rohleder on relentless remarketing - customers will buy from competitors if you don't stay in front of them. Most people don't go far enough with frequency. Session 7.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-097\"\n        statement: \"Don't be afraid to go over the top. People have built an immunity almost like insects build immunity to poison. You have to go over the top just to break through that resistance.\"\n        context: \"TJ Rohleder comparing customer resistance to marketing messages to how insects build immunity to pesticides - you need to escalate your promises to break through. Session 7.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"PHI-RB-098\"\n        statement: \"The death of one's identity is very often a lot more frightening than physical death. Hence, suicides. Rose in Titanic would rather jump into the sea than leave her identity.\"\n        context: \"Michael Hauge explaining why transformation is so hard for customers - stepping out of their identity feels like death because they believe their identity IS who they really are. Session 10.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_10.txt\"\n```\n\n## L2 MENTAL MODELS (MM-RB-074 through MM-RB-082)\n\n```yaml\n      - id: \"MM-RB-074\"\n        name: \"Identity vs Essence Model\"\n        description: \"Every person has an 'identity' (false self/emotional armor created to protect from past wounds) and an 'essence' (their true potential self). The inner journey is moving from identity to essence. Customers resist because their identity keeps them safe but unfulfilled. From Michael Hauge's Heroes Two Journeys framework.\"\n        application: \"In marketing stories and sales processes, recognize that the customer's resistance is their identity protecting them. Show the aftermath (life in their essence) to create passion that trumps the fear of transformation. Ask: 'I'll do whatever it takes to achieve my goal - just don't ask me to ___' to find the identity block.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_10.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"MM-RB-075\"\n        name: \"Wound-Belief-Fear-Identity Chain\"\n        description: \"A painful past experience (wound) creates a belief about how the world works, which instills a fear, which causes the person to create an identity (emotional armor). Beliefs from wounds are never accurate but always logical. From Michael Hauge.\"\n        application: \"When crafting customer avatars and stories, trace the chain: What wound did they suffer? What belief did that create? What fear does that belief instill? What identity/false self did they build? Then design the story to help them shed that identity and step into their essence.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_10.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"MM-RB-076\"\n        name: \"Belief Installation Model\"\n        description: \"The purpose of a story in marketing is not to convince people the product is great, but to install a single simple belief. Once they have that belief, the product sells itself - they've been waiting for you to offer it. From Dagan Smith's Story Selling.\"\n        application: \"Before writing any sales story, identify the ONE simple belief the audience needs to adopt. Build the entire story around installing and reinforcing that belief. The product reveal becomes natural because the audience already wants the solution to realize the belief.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_8.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"MM-RB-077\"\n        name: \"Internet Abundance Principle\"\n        description: \"There's more than enough for everybody to have more than enough and there'd still be more than enough left over. Addresses the objection 'if this is so good why are you selling it?' Three rebuttals: 1) Abundance - helping you make money helps me make money, 2) Public service - I was so frustrated it took so long to learn, I want to share, 3) Scale - I need other people to do my trainings. From TJ Rohleder and Myron Golden.\"\n        application: \"Use this three-part rebuttal framework whenever prospects question why you'd share a profitable system rather than keep it to yourself. Address the self-interest angle credibly.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"MM-RB-078\"\n        name: \"Five Turning Point Cave Model\"\n        description: \"From Michael Hauge: In any customer journey, there are 5 predictable turning points (at roughly 10%, 25%, 50%, 75%, and 90% of the journey) where people are most likely to back out. These correspond to: opportunity presented, change of plans, point of no return, major setback, and climax. Each is a moment of fear where identity resists change.\"\n        application: \"Map your customer's journey from first hearing about you to fully succeeding with your program. Identify the 5 cave points where they're most likely to quit. Prepare interventions at each point that instill passion (showing the aftermath) to overcome fear.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_10.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"MM-RB-079\"\n        name: \"Attractive Character Through Vulnerability\"\n        description: \"The most powerful way to build trust and become an attractive character is by strategically revealing personal flaws and failures. People are drawn to imperfect, real humans - not polished perfect images. Your story of struggle IS your greatest marketing asset. From John Alanis and TJ Rohleder.\"\n        application: \"Gradually reveal personal struggles, failures, and flaws in your marketing. Start small and test audience response. The positive spin (how you overcame it) makes it powerful. Test your 'colorful language' and personal revelations with live audiences before using in copy.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_5.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"MM-RB-080\"\n        name: \"Emotional Hook Discovery\"\n        description: \"Every offer has one emotional hook buried in it that makes people unable to stop thinking about it - like a song stuck in your head. The hook is often already there in the product/company's copy, you just need to find it and amplify it. From TJ Rohleder's example of finding 'get paid thousands of times a day' buried in affiliate program copy.\"\n        application: \"When creating offers, search through all existing copy and materials for that one sentence or idea that creates an emotional response. Extract it, amplify it into the headline. 'As long as it sounds good' - the hook must be emotionally compelling, not logically perfect.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"MM-RB-081\"\n        name: \"Reflection Character Role\"\n        description: \"From Michael Hauge: In every hero's journey, there must be a 'reflection character' (sidekick) who supports the hero's outer goal while holding their feet to the fire on inner transformation. In marketing, YOU are the reflection character for your customer - helping them achieve their goal while forcing them to face the truth about what's really stopping them.\"\n        application: \"Position yourself in your marketing and coaching as the reflection character. Support their external goal (make money, lose weight) while gently confronting the identity blocks stopping them. Like Donkey to Shrek - help with the quest but say 'what are you really afraid of?'\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_10.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"MM-RB-082\"\n        name: \"Inception Writing Model\"\n        description: \"From Russell Brunson's presentation titled 'Inception' - based on the movie concept. Instead of overtly selling, structure words and language patterns to plant ideas in the prospect's mind so they believe the idea is their own. You're not giving them a belief - they must accept it themselves. The emphasis is on the idea, not the product.\"\n        application: \"Structure all copy and presentations so the prospect arrives at the desired conclusion on their own. Use language patterns, nested stories, and strategic reveals so the 'aha moment' feels self-discovered rather than imposed. The product becomes the natural next step after the idea takes root.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_2.txt\"\n```\n\n## L3 HEURISTICS (HEUR-RB-122 through HEUR-RB-131)\n\n```yaml\n      - id: \"HEUR-RB-122\"\n        rule: \"Just asking for $1 changes everything. A $1 qualifier dramatically increases lead quality even though it reduces volume.\"\n        threshold: \"$1 minimum qualifier\"\n        context: \"TJ Rohleder sharing the story of buying Profit Ideas from Russ Von Holtscher - removing the $1 qualifier increased leads but decreased quality. Just $1 creates emotional commitment. Session 7.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"HEUR-RB-123\"\n        rule: \"Test every new offer to your best customers first. If your best customers don't get super excited about it, forget it. Then test down through customer segments.\"\n        threshold: \"Best customers must show excitement before broader rollout\"\n        context: \"TJ Rohleder on offer validation - segment your customer list into 4 levels, test with best customers first, then work down. Use best customers as guinea pigs. Session 7.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"HEUR-RB-124\"\n        rule: \"For the content webinar supporting the Invisible Funnel, include: images, stories, demonstrations, case studies, logic, news, and history. These elements support the offer being made.\"\n        threshold: \"7 content elements minimum\"\n        context: \"Russell Brunson listing the elements he ensures are in every content webinar for the Invisible Funnel - not selling on the webinar but making it an experience that supports the offer. Session 3.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_3.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"HEUR-RB-125\"\n        rule: \"In story selling, the epiphany must be something SIMPLE - one word, one receipt, one concept. It can't be 'I discovered the theory of relativity.' People need it to be simple to accept it.\"\n        threshold: \"One simple idea/word/concept as the epiphany\"\n        context: \"Dagan Smith emphasizing that the story's turning point must be extremely simple for the audience to believe they can replicate it. His example: 'co-op' - one word changed everything. Session 8.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_8.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"HEUR-RB-126\"\n        rule: \"Never let more than 100 people get involved in one co-op. Limit it to what you can manage, then pass it off to someone else on your team.\"\n        threshold: \"100 people maximum per co-op\"\n        context: \"Dagan Smith sharing operational rules for running marketing co-ops - keeping groups manageable. Also: never let members buy multiple shares, facilitate their growth but don't finance it. Session 8.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_8.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"HEUR-RB-127\"\n        rule: \"When writing emotional copy, never state emotions passively ('I was depressed'). Instead, share mental thoughts, physical sensations, and the experience: 'My heart sunk. All I could think was, why me?'\"\n        threshold: \"3 elements: mental thoughts + physical sensations + experience\"\n        context: \"Dagan Smith teaching how to make audiences FEEL emotions in written stories - passive emotion labeling doesn't work, active experiential description does. Session 8.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_8.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"HEUR-RB-128\"\n        rule: \"With the right offer, even a 'dead' crowd will buy. When his team said 'this crowd is dead, they won't buy anything,' TJ kept stacking the offer until they sold almost everybody at $3,000-$4,000.\"\n        threshold: \"Stack the offer until resistance breaks\"\n        context: \"TJ Rohleder sharing the San Diego seminar story where his 20-year veteran said the crowd wouldn't buy - they brainstormed additional bonuses and value until it became irresistible and sold almost everyone. Session 7.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"HEUR-RB-129\"\n        rule: \"In story selling, use case studies to 'throw the basketball' - detach the epiphany idea from yourself so the audience can own it. Without case studies, they think 'that's awesome for YOU but won't work for ME.'\"\n        threshold: \"Minimum 3 case studies showing the idea works for others\"\n        context: \"Dagan Smith explaining the basketball analogy - an idea is like a ball you must throw to the audience. Case studies are how you transfer ownership of the idea from your story to their reality. Session 8.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_8.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"HEUR-RB-130\"\n        rule: \"Segment your customer list into at least 4 levels. Most marketing will fail on the bottom segments but keep testing and 'keep hope alive.' Focus energy on best customers first.\"\n        threshold: \"4 customer segments minimum\"\n        context: \"TJ Rohleder on customer segmentation - from best buyers to $9-only buyers. Different offers work for different segments. Some segments barely respond but you keep trying. Session 7.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"HEUR-RB-131\"\n        rule: \"Create a 'better than no risk' guarantee - not just money back, but they keep everything AND get their money back. They don't even have to send it back.\"\n        threshold: \"Guarantee must be BETTER than risk-free, not just risk-free\"\n        context: \"TJ Rohleder on his $2,500 offer where customers have 30 days to decide, keep all materials regardless, and can cut him out completely and make money on their own with the materials. Session 7.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n```\n\n## L4 FRAMEWORKS (FW-RB-077 through FW-RB-084)\n\n```yaml\n      - id: \"FW-RB-077\"\n        name: \"Story Selling Architecture (Dagan Smith)\"\n        components: \"1. High Drama (display an insurmountable wall) â†’ 2. One Simple Epiphany (one word/idea changes everything) â†’ 3. New Possibilities (cascade of good ideas from the one idea) â†’ 4. Hero's Choice (decide to act despite fear) â†’ 5. First Signs of Success â†’ 6. Rapid Growth â†’ 7. Case Studies (detach idea from you - throw the basketball) â†’ 8. Hidden Benefits (what people don't see is even better) â†’ 9. Objection Transformation (turn objections into reasons to say yes) â†’ 10. Allude to Twist (something even bigger) â†’ 11. Mistakes to Avoid (inoculate) â†’ 12. Ultimate Solution Reveal â†’ 13. Pain of Inaction Bridge â†’ 14. Invitation (Invisible Funnel proposition)\"\n        application: \"Use this 14-step structure for content webinars, sales letters, email sequences, and any story-based selling. The goal is to install a belief through story, not sell a product. Product sells itself once belief is installed. Can be split across two webinars (story + content).\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_8.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"FW-RB-078\"\n        name: \"Heroes Two Journeys (Michael Hauge)\"\n        components: \"OUTER JOURNEY (6 stages): 1. Setup (10%) â†’ 2. New Situation (25%) â†’ 3. Progress (50% - Point of No Return) â†’ 4. Complications & Higher Stakes (75%) â†’ 5. Major Setback â†’ 6. Climax + Aftermath. INNER JOURNEY (parallel): Identity â†’ Glimpse of Essence â†’ Vacillation between Identity/Essence â†’ Commitment to Essence â†’ Retreat to Identity after setback â†’ Final push into Essence â†’ Aftermath showing new life. Five turning points at 10%, 25%, 50%, 75%, 90%.\"\n        application: \"Structure every marketing story with both an outer journey (external events) and an inner journey (emotional transformation from identity to essence). The outer journey hooks attention; the inner journey creates deep identification and desire for transformation. Always include the aftermath - show the new life.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_9.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"FW-RB-079\"\n        name: \"TJ Rohleder's 8-Step Perfect Offer Formula\"\n        components: \"1. Premium Pricing (price reflects transformation value) â†’ 2. Make Sure It Was Just For Them (exclusivity/personalization) â†’ 3. Giant Promises (go over the top, back with proof) â†’ 4. Better Than No-Risk Guarantee (they keep everything even if they refund) â†’ 5. Relentless Follow-Up (constant contact, new angles weekly) â†’ 6. Salespeople (someone to build rapport and close) â†’ 7. Your Story & Emotional Factors (let your guard down, reveal flaws) â†’ 8. Events/Interaction (seminars, webinars, phone calls with customers)\"\n        application: \"Apply all 8 elements when constructing any high-ticket offer. Stack them until resistance breaks. The 'reason why' offer (beta tester model) gives a credible reason for the deal. Test to best customers first, then work down through segments.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"FW-RB-080\"\n        name: \"Attractive Character Email Framework (John Alanis)\"\n        components: \"1. Create an Attractive Character persona to speak from â†’ 2. Send 2 emails per day (frequency is king) â†’ 3. Use colorful language modeled from those who are good at it â†’ 4. Test statements with live audiences, discard what doesn't work, keep what does (Marx Brothers method) â†’ 5. Be self-interested transparently (most credible motivation) â†’ 6. Tie dating/relationship dynamics to marketing (desire systems are universal)\"\n        application: \"Build an attractive character persona for your email marketing. Send high-frequency emails with personality. Model colorful language from great communicators. The dating-to-marketing parallel: attracting customers uses the same psychological principles as attracting romantic partners. John Alanis applied dating psychology to double and then quadruple his business.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_4.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"FW-RB-081\"\n        name: \"Beta Tester Offer Method (TJ Rohleder)\"\n        components: \"1. Position the offer as needing 'beta testers to get the bugs out' â†’ 2. Explain that more participants = better testing â†’ 3. Structure as affiliate/JV where you profit by helping them profit â†’ 4. Use 'reason why' copy explaining the special pricing â†’ 5. Better-than-risk-free guarantee â†’ 6. Done-for-you elements with one missing ingredient the customer provides\"\n        application: \"When launching a new product or program, frame it as a beta test. This addresses the 'if it's so good why sell it' objection naturally. The beta framing creates urgency, exclusivity, and a credible reason for aggressive pricing. TJ mailed millions of these pieces over 15-17 years successfully.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"FW-RB-082\"\n        name: \"Two-Part Invisible Funnel Webinar Structure\"\n        components: \"Part 1 (Story Webinar): Tell story using Story Selling Architecture â†’ install belief â†’ create desire â†’ invite to Part 2 with Invisible Funnel proposition (don't pay now, experience it first). Part 2 (Content Webinar): Deliver massive value â†’ if they love it, keep it and pay; if not, walk away. Part 1 emails: short story hook emails driving to registration. Part 1 registration page: just the story hook, no product pitch.\"\n        application: \"Split the selling process into two events. Part 1 does the belief installation via story (higher show-up for Part 2 because desire is built). Part 2 delivers content with Invisible Funnel model. Dagan's stats: 1,100 registered for Part 1, 500 registered for Part 2 from Part 1. Can also be done as email series â†’ single webinar.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_8.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"FW-RB-083\"\n        name: \"Russell Brunson's 7-Step Lifeline of a Lead\"\n        components: \"Step 1: Lead capture (squeeze page) â†’ Step 2: Immediate indoctrination (who you are, what you stand for) â†’ Step 3: Content delivery with embedded selling â†’ Step 4: Core offer presentation â†’ Step 5: Upsell/downsell sequence â†’ Step 6: Follow-up sequence (ongoing) â†’ Step 7: High-ticket application/phone close. Focus on conversion at each micro-step, not just the funnel as a whole. Split test every element.\"\n        application: \"Map every lead's journey from first touch through highest-ticket offer. Optimize conversion at each individual step. Russell's focus: the structure of the sales process and conversion optimization at each stage, including landing page split tests and micro-conversion improvements.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_14.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"FW-RB-084\"\n        name: \"Chapter-Based Story Launch Sequence\"\n        components: \"1. Write a full story-based sales letter â†’ 2. Split it into chapters â†’ 3. Release one chapter per day via email â†’ 4. Add opt-in box at end of each chapter: 'opt in to get Chapter N+1 before everyone else' â†’ 5. Build anticipation across multiple days â†’ 6. Final chapter reveals the offer. Creates serial engagement like a TV show.\"\n        application: \"Instead of sending one long sales letter, serialize it into a multi-day story-driven launch. Each chapter builds desire and commitment. The opt-in for 'early access to next chapter' creates micro-commitments and builds the launch list within the launch. Dagan's early career success with this format.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_8.txt\"\n```\n\n## L5 METHODOLOGIES (MET-RB-042 through MET-RB-047)\n\n```yaml\n      - id: \"MET-RB-042\"\n        name: \"Story Selling Content Assembly Method (Dagan Smith)\"\n        steps: \"1. Define the ONE simple belief you want to install â†’ 2. Brainstorm all content: benefits, objections, case studies, hidden benefits, mistakes â†’ 3. Label each piece: HB (hidden benefit), RB (regular benefit), objection, case study, content â†’ 4. Map each piece to the Story Selling Architecture stages (where does it fit best?) â†’ 5. Arrange into story flow diagram with hero's journey as spine â†’ 6. Identify the 'insurmountable object' moment (most important) â†’ 7. Test in Facebook live/webinar format â†’ 8. Ask audience questions during delivery: 'What was the biggest benefit? What was your biggest objection? Do you feel we handled it?' â†’ 9. Require minimum 20 audience answers before moving on\"\n        application: \"Use this assembly method before building any story-based webinar or sales letter. Get all ideas out first (brainstorm), then organize them into the story structure. The brainstorm-then-organize approach prevents writer's block and ensures nothing important is missed.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_8.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"MET-RB-043\"\n        name: \"Michael Hauge's Story Character Construction Method\"\n        steps: \"1. Define hero's LONGING (deeply held desire they pay lip service to but are too afraid to pursue) or NEED (something missing they won't even admit to themselves) â†’ 2. Identify the WOUND (painful past experience they believe they've left behind but still determines behavior) â†’ 3. Derive the BELIEF (always logical but never accurate belief about how the world works, born from the wound) â†’ 4. Name the FEAR (fear of suffering the wound's pain again) â†’ 5. Construct the IDENTITY (false self/emotional armor created to protect from the fear) â†’ 6. Define the ESSENCE (who they have the potential to become if they find the courage - their truth) â†’ 7. The story rule: hero must move from identity to essence to win; if they stay in identity, it's a tragedy\"\n        application: \"Apply to both your own origin story and customer avatar creation. The customer's identity is what resists your offer. Your marketing must help them see their essence (the after picture) and create enough passion to overcome the fear of shedding their identity. Every testimonial should show the identity-to-essence transformation.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_10.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"MET-RB-044\"\n        name: \"Invisible Funnel Content Webinar Design Method\"\n        steps: \"1. Create the offer FIRST (what you'll sell on the back end) â†’ 2. Ask: 'How can I support that offer in the content webinar?' â†’ 3. Include these 7 elements: images, stories, demonstrations, case studies, logic, news, history â†’ 4. Create outline with each element mapped to offer support â†’ 5. Design the content as an EXPERIENCE (not a product pitch) â†’ 6. They should 'love it and feel like they leave with a lot of value' â†’ 7. Content webinar proposition: 'Don't pay now. Experience it. If you love it, keep it. If not, walk away.' â†’ 8. Follow up with continuity/high-ticket offer\"\n        application: \"When building an Invisible Funnel, start with the back-end offer and work backwards to design content that naturally makes people want that offer. The content itself is the sales mechanism - not a pitch within the content. Russell's distinction: this is not how you'd think about a regular product, it's an experience.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_3.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"MET-RB-045\"\n        name: \"TJ Rohleder's Offer Stack Brainstorm Method\"\n        steps: \"1. Assess the crowd/audience energy and resistance level â†’ 2. If resistance is high, gather your best people for emergency brainstorm â†’ 3. Start with your initial offer â†’ 4. Each person suggests additional value/bonuses to stack â†’ 5. Create a 'pissing championship' dynamic where each person tries to top the previous suggestion â†’ 6. Keep stacking until the offer is so good it's 'kind of ridiculous' â†’ 7. If you can't present it all yourself, hand off to team member ('let Chris explain the rest') â†’ 8. Deliver with passion and make it feel personal â†’ 9. Result: sell almost everyone, even a 'dead' crowd\"\n        application: \"When preparing for any sales presentation, especially live events, always over-prepare the offer stack. The brainstorm-stack-compete method generates more value than any individual could think of alone. Surround yourself with passionate team members for these sessions. Test at tail end of sessions when the 'engine is warmed up.'\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_7.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"MET-RB-046\"\n        name: \"Active Emotion Writing Technique (Dagan Smith)\"\n        steps: \"1. Identify the emotion you want the reader to feel (excitement, fear, devastation, triumph) â†’ 2. Journal: what does this emotion PHYSICALLY feel like? (hands got cold, mouth went dry, tingling feeling) â†’ 3. Journal: what are the MENTAL THOUGHTS during this emotion? (I think this is it. Why me?) â†’ 4. Reconstruct the EXPERIENCE with sensory details (what you saw, heard, where you were) â†’ 5. Write the scene by combining all three: physical sensations + mental thoughts + experiential details â†’ 6. NEVER state the emotion passively ('I was depressed') â†’ 7. Instead bring reader INTO the situation: 'When I opened the letter, immediately my heart sunk. All I could think was, why me?'\"\n        application: \"Use this technique for every emotional moment in sales copy, stories, and content. Practice by journaling about your own emotional experiences. Capture what happiness, excitement, fear, devastation physically feel like. Build a library of emotional descriptions you can deploy in copy.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_8.txt\"\n\n      - id: \"MET-RB-047\"\n        name: \"Jimmy Davis High-Ticket Phone Close Process\"\n        steps: \"1. Application/qualification before the call (filter for serious prospects) â†’ 2. Build rapport on the call - personal connection first â†’ 3. Diagnose their situation using questions (don't pitch immediately) â†’ 4. Use the 'one missing ingredient' positioning - they have everything except this one thing â†’ 5. Present the high-ticket offer as the missing piece â†’ 6. Handle objections using reframing (turn objections into positive reasons to say yes) â†’ 7. Close with urgency and exclusivity â†’ 8. Follow up relentlessly post-close. Russell described Jimmy's closing process as 'some of the coolest stuff I've ever seen' for high-ticket.\"\n        application: \"Apply this process for closing $3,000-$25,000+ offers by phone. The key insight is diagnosis before prescription - ask questions to understand their situation, then position your offer as the solution to their specific diagnosed problem. Jimmy Davis learned from Glazer-Kennedy and adapted for high-ticket internet marketing.\"\n        module_sources: [IF-WORKSHOP]\n        raw_source: \"knowledge/sources/russell-brunson/raw/08._Funnel_Immersion/Invisible Funnel/Invisible Funnel Workshop/transcription_Session_15.txt\"\n```\n\n---\n\nThat completes the DNA extraction from all 15 Invisible Funnel Workshop sessions. Summary of elements extracted:\n\n| Layer | Count | ID Range Used |\n|-------|-------|---------------|\n| L1 PHILOSOPHIES | 12 | PHI-RB-087 through PHI-RB-098 |\n| L2 MENTAL MODELS | 9 | MM-RB-074 through MM-RB-082 |\n| L3 HEURISTICS | 10 | HEUR-RB-122 through HEUR-RB-131 |\n| L4 FRAMEWORKS | 8 | FW-RB-077 through FW-RB-084 |\n| L5 METHODOLOGIES | 6 | MET-RB-042 through MET-RB-047 |\n| **TOTAL** | **45 elements** | |\n\nKey speakers covered:\n- **Russell Brunson** (Sessions 1, 2, 3, 14) - Invisible Funnel structure, Inception writing, sales process architecture, split testing\n- **Dagan Smith** (Sessions 2, 3, 8, 12) - Story Selling Architecture, belief installation, active emotion writing\n- **Michael Hauge** (Sessions 9, 10, 13) - Heroes Two Journeys, identity vs essence, wound-belief-fear chain, character construction\n- **TJ Rohleder** (Session 7) - 8-Step Offer Formula, beta tester method, offer stacking, better-than-risk-free guarantee\n- **John Alanis** (Sessions 4, 5) - Attractive Character, email marketing, dating-to-marketing parallel, colorful language\n- **Jimmy Davis** (Session 15) - High-ticket phone closing process</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>132044</total_tokens><tool_uses>20</tool_uses><duration_ms>314586</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: C:\\Users\\ISMAEL~1\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\claude\\C--Users-ISMAEL-MELLO-Downloads-mega-brain-premium\\tasks\\aeb11c5b66d9c9329.output"}, "_timestamp": "2026-03-07T19:23:46.607107", "_id": "643d57d2"}
